<DOC><DOCNO> AP891201-0083 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 2105EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Memorial     12-01 0231</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Peru-Memorial,0236</SECOND><HEAD>Memorial Erected to Wife of Jersey City, N.J., Mayor</HEAD><DATELINE>CUZCO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The city erected a memorial Friday to thewife of a New Jersey mayor killed a year ago when a train carryingher and her husband was derailed by saboteurs.   Anna Cucci was killed and her husband, then-Mayor Anthony Cucciof Jersey City, N.J., was injured when the rail car they wereriding in tumbled down a 250-foot ravine near Cuzco, 355 milessoutheast of Lima in the Andes Mountains.   The monument christened Friday also commemorates the wife ofCuzco's mayor, Doris Mayorga de Chacon, who also was killed. Themonument was erected in the Plaza of American Brotherhood indowntown Cuzco.   The rail car was derailed when it hit a 10-inch steel rod wedgedinto the tracks. Authorities said the rod probably was placed byleftist rebels or striking rail workers. No one has been charged inthe deaths.   The Cuccis were visiting Cuzco to sign a sister city accordbetween Jersey City and Cuzco. Six other people were injured whenthe car derailed on its way to the ancient Incan citadel of MachuPicchu, located 60 miles northwest of Cuzco.   Mayor Carlos Chacon, who was injured in the derailment, presidedat a ceremony unveiling the two plaques, one in English and one inSpanish. Chacon called the two women ``martyrs of Americanbrotherhood.''</TEXT></DOC>